â€œThe EU AI Act classifies artificial intelligence systems into four risk levels.
	1.	Unacceptable-risk AI
These are banned entirely. Examples include social credit scoring or AI that manipulates vulnerable groups.
	2.	High-risk AI
These systems are allowed but must meet strict safety standards. This includes AI used in healthcare, transportation, employment, education, and law enforcement. Companies must conduct risk assessments, maintain data quality, and ensure human oversight.
	3.	Limited-risk AI
Systems like chatbots must clearly inform users they are interacting with AI.
	4.	Minimal-risk AI
Most everyday toolsâ€”like AI filters or game AIsâ€”fall here.

The Act holds companies legally responsible for misuse, discrimination, and harmful outcomes. This is a major shift because many countries still rely on voluntary guidelines instead of laws.â€

